WOW! I love Gary Danko!!! This was an amazing experience and I cannot wait until the next big occasion so we have an excuse to go back! Amuse Bouche: Vegan winter soup. yummy First Course: Lobster risotta with rock shrimp - huge portion and so good!! Frisee salad with crispy egg and bacon: Um, how can you go wrong? Second Course: Marinated pork with pork belly - the 12 hr marinated pork, mashed potatoes, and pickled jalapenos were to die for. I was unimpressed by the pork belly Steak with bone marrow butter: Best thing I have ever tasted! Third Course: Cheese - great selection Fourth Course: Macaron ice cream sandwiches - with homemade sauces!! Chocolate Souffle - good but again unimpressed. Maybe because I was so stuffed! Portions are huge and this is well worth the price! We got a mini dessert tray at the end of the meal which we took home with a breakfast pumpkin brioche. The next morning was good to say the least :) If you have the chance to eat here, GO!

My 300th review! :D There are a few meals that I've had that has changed my life and how I look at food, being 8 and eating my first piece of uni, being 12 and cracking the crust on my first creme brulee and traveling in Japan and eating skewered BBQ meats in a narrow, dark, smokey alley. This is one of those moments. I took my g/f here to celebrate a special occasion, and we were warmly greeted by our hostess, we ate light through the day so we could save room and savor each bite of the meal to come. We ended up arriving about a half hour early but they seated us anyways. Our waiter was a really friendly and personable guy by the name of Cole. He was very professional and made sure everything was to our liking, while keeping the mood the evening unpretentious and warm. It felt like I was eating in at a close friends house. The menu was very extensive, I was impressed with the ambition of a chef to go and ahead make such an extensive menu, I mean not including the cheese cart, there were 12 choices for appetizers, fish & seafood 7 choices, meat & game 8 choices and dessert 9 choices. Cole informed us we could order a 3, 4 or 5 course meal and we can pick what ever we want off of it, so if you want 4 starters and a dessert you could do that, hell you could even go and do a 5 course dessert if you want, he did mention that doing more then 2 meat & game dishes will be done but advised against it as those dishes are especially heavy. I was thinking in my head this chef must be mad, because I'm imagining all timing that needs to be done for cooking and other logistics that can come up in the kitchen but to time them with the rest of the order seemed almost overwhelming. After much deliberation and thinking we finally made up our minds. My meal: Dungenous crab salad with citrus, avocado, and Meyer lemon chive vinaigrette. Roast Maine lobster with potato puree, shitake mushrooms, corn and tarragon Roasted Loin of Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spatzle Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream The dishes were beautifully done, each one had a unique and different flavor, they were amazing. The lemon and chive vinaigrette on paper caught me off guard, I didn't expect it to have such a mild herbiness brought about by the lemon zest and chives, it went perfect with the crab. Roasted Lobster and mushrooms, individually I love love each of them, on one plate and making it so I don't have to get my hands dirty eating lobster, even better! The roasted bison dish was very heavy but very moist and didn't have any gaminess, the spatzle and mushrooms once again made my tummy happy. The dessert blew me away, buttery and rich, but with a sweet and little tart huckleberries against the creaminess of the ice cream. An amazing end to the meal. Her Meal: Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms and lemon soy dressing Mushroom dusted sea scallops with English pea puree, shimeji mushrooms and Meyer lemon Quail stuffed with foie gras, leeks and quinoa, farro, maitake mushrooms, zucchini and roasted red pepper. Baked Chocolate souffle with 2 sauces I only got a few bites here and there on these dishes as I was busy eating my own meal, but from what I tasted the quail and the sea scallop dishes is what really stood out. The quail was moist, had a wonderful aroma and a great richness to it, no hint of gaminess at all. The scallops were perfectly cooked, keeping that moist and subtle sweetness that I love. The puree provided a nice color presentation and contributed a nice flavor to the dish as well. The cheese course was awesome, mind you we were both getting extremely full, and we saw the generous wedges of the cheese they were giving to everyone, and we knew we couldn't eat that much since we had dessert coming, and we had no idea what to pick, we asked if it would be OK if we got a small little taste on most of the cheeses. I think we ended up with 8 or 9 cheeses all of them great but at this point we were so full and getting a little food coma-ish, I couldn't remember for the life of me their names. I'll just say, if you haven't done a cheese course, definitely do it here. The meal as a whole was amazing, we took our time eating, and the 1st dish came out pretty quickly, but in between it was a very well timed spacing in between the courses, so we could have time to talk and digest our food. Also after our dessert course because it was a special occasion they gave us another complementary dessert, it was this lemon mouse dessert, that one was amazing, I liked it even more then the chocolate souffle that my g/f had ordered. Too bad it's not on the menu, I would order that every time! After we settled the bill, they boxed up the little sweets that we were to full at the time to consume and gave us a take home cheesecake. I can't wait to go back. This experienced was a new measuring stick for how I view food!

2000+ rave reviews on yelp?! My expectations were set high -- perhaps a little too high. Or maybe I've just been spoiled by the other fine dining experiences we've had. We were super excited after securing a reservation 2 months in advance for my husband's birthday trip into SF. The restaurant itself is elegantly decorated, but not quite the quiet romantic evening that I was anticipating. The overall noise level is moderately high for a fine establishment and the tables are fairly close together - so you better hope for courteous non-obnoxious neighbors. I also found it odd there were only two single use bathrooms - so each of the 3 times I had to visit, there was a line of 2-3 people waiting. Hmmm.... The service definitely stands out, as the team is there to make your dinner a true experience. It's impeccably provided by a well orchestrated, non-intrusive, but ever watchful team. Your bread plate is refilled with two fresh slices the second you're done. The wine pairings are brought out for you to taste just as your next course is being served. As we paid the check and walked out, without any prompting, my previously checked jacket was held out by the hostess for me to step right into. If we had a valet car, it would've been pulled up front as we stepped outside. And they send you off with a fresh baked treat for breakfast the next morning! Now the food. The food is delicious and I love that you're free to choose whatever 3,4, or 5-course meal you desire. Others have commented that the portions are generous, but I wish I had thought to order more than a 3-course appetizer/entree/dessert as I left a little hungry despite taking many many bites from my husband's courses! (Perhaps next time I'll just order 4 entrees and a dessert.) I got: 1. Foie gras - Melt in your mouth delicious! 2. The famed roast Maine lobster and potato puree - Delicious, but the itty bitty lobster was a little disappointing. And unfortunately I've been spoiled by Joel Robuchon's heavenly mashed potatoes. 3. Chocolate soufflé - this was probably the biggest disappointment as it was so small (size of a mug) and not the rich flavor I was hoping for. (If you're ever in NYC, La Grenouille has the best/biggest chocolate souffle) He got: 1. Dungenness crab salad - tasty meaty fresh crab. 2. Branzini - fish that I've never heard of but was perfectly cooked with crispy skin. 3. Pork belly and tenderloin - moist and full of flavor. 4. Beef filet - As someone who loves her steak, this was also nothing special but good. All complemented by perfect wine pairings. Was it good? Yes. Was it out of this world? No. Is it worth the bill? I can think of other places I'd rather go. Will we be back? Jury's still out on that one.

My girlfriends and I made dinner reservations at Gary Danko for our best friend's birthday celebration. It was the perfect place for the four of us to catch-up while enjoying dinner and delicious cocktails in an intimate, elegant setting. Upon arrival the staff was very accommodating. Our service was of the highest caliber and the food was impeccable. From appetizers through entrées and desserts, we all fell in love with every single bite. Since I don't have too much of a sweet tooth, I was very happy to see that I was able to substitute a cheese course in place of dessert. Everything was perfect! I recommend Gary Danko to anyone searching for an intimate evening out or an elegant dinner with great friends. It's perfect for special occasions like a romantic date or anniversary, too. If you're in search of beautifully presented dishes that melt in your mouth, outstanding service, an extensive wine list or refreshing hand-crafted cocktail, this is definitely a place that comes highly recommended.

Four. Not five. Four. Stream of consciousness review...and...go! Warning: Lobster risotto = very cheesy. Lovely pumpkin breakfast bread to take home. In the restroom, shoe shine and Gary Danko stickers on the toilet paper rolls. Small dining room = hard reservation. Even so, calling Monday for a Tuesday reservation worked out! Laaaarge portions of good food. Incredible souffle. Is that guy wearing jeans??????????? Dining room not as eye-popping as Jean-Georges. Heck, overall, not as eye-popping as Jean-Georges, period.

Service. Like secrets agents prowling every step of the President, the wait staff is attentive, in a good way. Returning from a break to the wash room, my white table cloth napkin is folded. The bathroom is an experience in itself. Looking like a gala bathroom at a showcase South of Market, it provides a Zen like ambiance before the feast. With a smile and excitement, the wait staff explains dishes and readily available for suggestions. Danko is a great spot to wow your date with out the over the top gala of Ritz Carlton Dining Room. hint: When ordering at fine dining restaurant, choose dishes that you would not make at home. Take the chef for a test drive. Also, use ingredients that you may not prepare yourself. For Fear Factor thrill seekers, try the frog legs that don't disappoint. Unlike Michael Minna's, Danko has a menu that lets you be the boss. We each ordered the 3 course menu. You can order two main entrees and one appetizer if you feel like opting out on dessert. That's classy. I would best describe the cuisine as French with hints of Californian. For cheese lovers, don't miss out on their extensive cheese menu. Food. Prices are reasonable. (3 courses-$65,4 courses-$81, 5-courses$96) Dining with four people total, we order an array of dishes so that we can taste a myriad of flavors and textures. The foie gras makes me cry on the inside. With a velvety rich texture, it literally melts in your mouth. The pungent taste overwhelmed the palate while the after taste echoes throughout all the pivot points in your mouth. With a slight crispy crust, the frog legs were meaty and charmingly supported with lentil. The frog legs are a far cry from your the ones wok-fried in Chinatown. Stealing the appetizer show, the lobster risotto put me in comfort food heaven. With a creamy consistency, the see sweet lobster provided bouncy crunch that was a marriage made in heaven. The quail stuffed with mushroom and foie gras was another of my favorite dishes. Assemble small portion of earthy mushroom combined with buttery foie gras- all stuffed inside a moist quail. The result, amazingly. The savory sauce rounded out the dish.

Gary Danko. Gary Mother Fuckin' Danko. It goes without saying that our experience with Gary was flawless perfection. If a gay unicorn swinging from a rainbow shit Skittles into your mouth it could not be more magical than dining at Gary Danko. We made our reservation 2 months in advanced and the build up could not have been more pressurized. The fact that GD exceeded my incredibly high expectations speaks volumes. As you approach the restaurant the underplayed theme and the blacked out windows give you a supreme sense of entitlement. It's like GD begins to spoil you before you even walk through the door. The doorman, hosts, waitstaff, sommelier, and affineur were flawless, humble, friendly and perfect. They make you feel so welcome. They treat every selection that you make off the menu as the best selection of the evening (and you BELIEVE them whole heartedly). I love food. In fact, that is an understatement, I worship food. But I have never known food like GD presented food. GD changed my life with the following 5 course meal: To Clean the pallet we were invited to start with Champagne and the Cauliflower puree and marinated endive. The puree was delectably creamy and flavorful. This was the perfect teaser and you are left waiting with baited breath to see what will happen next. We ordered two wines with dinner. First a lighter Pinot (Hirsch Vineyard 2007) then a more boisterous Syrah (2005). Both amazing recommendations from the sommelier. As my first I chose the Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, FrisÈe and Pancetta. The egg was a masterpiece, lightly breaded and perfectly cooked. When you broke the yolk it mixed beautifully with the white polenta for an amazingly rich texture and taste. The mushrooms in the dish where probably my favorite element, so flavorful and rich. For my second I choose the Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Brussels Sprouts, Bacon, Parsnip PurÈe and Maple Cider Glaze. The Pork Belly was hands down my favorite dish of the evening. The glaze was out of this world; it gave the crust on the meat the perfect crunch complimented by the buttery, tender, melt in your mouth meat that hit your tongue like heaven. My third was the Braised Lamb Shoulder and Herb Crusted Loin with Barley Stew, Red Pepper Relish and Cumin Yogurt. The barley was cooked to perfection; so tender with the perfect flavor to compliment the meat yet underwhelm the cumin yogurt. The cumin yogurt certainly carried this plate - it was delicious. The perfect bite of tender meat, barley and cumin yogurt was enough to pledge my future unwanted first born child to GD. The most awaited part of the evening for me was the much anticipated Cheese Cart. A Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside. I literally died and found heaven on this cheese cart. You get to choose 4 cheeses that are served with walnut raisin bread and fresh red grapes. I suggest that you and your dining partner each choose 4 different cheeses and then share accordingly. The cheese experience is amazing! And then there was dessert. How I had room for dessert, is beyond me, but how could you not? The French Macaron Ice Cream Sandwiches with Three Sauces was to die for sinful. I cannot put into words how amazing the cookies where, they where literally something I have never experienced before. You are served three mini sandwiches. They were crunchy, melty, gooey perfection. The ice cream was very mild in taste and the sauces complimented each cookie flavor perfectly. My favorite was the pistachio cookie with chocolate sauce. Divine. You think you are done, you cannot possible put one more bite of food into your mouth and you are expecting the bill, but no, instead your server places a silver platter of delicate hand made candies on your table and you groan out of pure satiated pain. Luckily, they understand how you feel at this point and they politely offer to wrap the candies up for you in the perfect to go container. BUT WAIT...they still aren't done completely impressing the fuck out of you. They also send you home with a gorgeously wrapped "breakfast bread." YOU HAVE GOT TO BE KIDDING ME! Oh, GD, you really think of everything! By the end of the meal you completely forget that you are paying to be here and you start to profusely thank everybody that has served you like they have done you a favor like no other favor ever done. I never wanted to leave! I thought that I would be leaving still hungry and considerably poorer (yet gloriously happy). WRONG. I was more stuffed than I have ever been in my life and when the bill came I was pleasantly less shocked than I had prepared myself for. This 2.5 hour, 5 course meal doesn't fuck around. GD certainly takes food VERY seriously, and I adore him for that. Once in a lifetime experience? Screw that! When can I go back???

3.5 stars rounding down to 3. We made a RSVP about 1.5 mo before and of course the only thing available on a Sat. night is 930pm. 1st thing I realized is how hidden it is. I've probably passed by it tons of times and never realized it was there. Add in the blackout windows and its only recognizable by a little plaque next to the front door. We were greeted warmly at the door and shown to our seat with just a moment's wait. My first impression was that the restaurant was a lot smaller than I thought. The second was that the decor was pretty simple and nothing spectacular. The third, and most annoying, was that the tables were VERY close to each other. This prompted servers bumping me with their ass every time they served the table next to me. That got annoying pretty quick. The menu was given to us and the server was very patient going over the choices, giving her recommendations, and answering our questions. We took about 15 minutes to decide while our amouse bouch (gazpacho) sat thankfully cold in front of us. Its nice to have so many choices and to choose anything on the menu as a course although not good for indecisive people like me. Finally we make our selections and begin salivating and what was to come. What we quickly noticed was that there were no more amouse bouch(es). I'm used to at least 3-4 throughout the meal but none showed up throughout the night. That was disappointing. What made up for it was the nice portion size of all the dishes. They were definitely hefty and we were pretty full by the time our 4th course came out (we had 5 each). This allowed us to share with each other more effectively and without feeling as bad ;) The food was good but not spectacular unfortunately. All the seafood dishes were fresh (Crab salad, broiled lobster, lobster risotto) but the meats were just ok (Pork belly, duck). Risotto was more watery than normal and pork belly seemed overcooked and didnt melt in my mouth. Dessert didnt save it either as the creme brule was very strong of liqueur and the cheesecake was more sour and too fluffy. About 2.5 hours later, and some great company, we finished our meal and surveyed the damage. The price is reasonable and typical for a 5 course "fancy" meal and again the portion size is what saved a star. However, the lack of originality and mediocre execution of the food, close tables, unexciting decor, and just average service adds up to a 3 star review.

Celebrated a birthday here recently and was pretty impressed with the food and service. We had the tasting menu sans the cheese course. Memorable course was the duck and the sea salt caramel dessert. Will definitely be back.

    3 check-ins

    My 300th review!  :D

    There are a few meals that I've had that has changed my life and how I look at food, being 8 and eating my first piece of uni, being 12 and cracking the crust on my first creme brulee  and traveling in Japan and eating skewered BBQ meats in a narrow, dark, smokey alley.  This is one of those moments.

    I took my g/f here to celebrate a special occasion, and we were warmly greeted by our hostess, we ate light through the day so we could save room and savor each bite of the meal to come.  We ended up arriving about a half hour early but they seated us anyways.  Our waiter was a really friendly and personable guy by the name of Cole.  He was very professional and made sure everything was to our liking, while keeping the mood the evening unpretentious and warm.  It felt like I was eating in at a close friends house.  The menu was very extensive, I was impressed with the ambition of a chef to go and ahead make such an extensive menu, I mean not including the cheese cart, there were 12 choices for appetizers, fish & seafood 7 choices, meat & game 8 choices and dessert 9 choices.  Cole informed us we could order a 3, 4 or 5 course meal and we can pick what ever we want off of it, so if you want 4 starters and a dessert you could do that, hell you could even go and do a 5 course dessert if you want, he did mention that doing more then 2 meat & game dishes will be done but advised against it as those dishes are especially heavy.  I was thinking in my head this chef must be mad, because I'm imagining all timing that needs to be done for cooking and other logistics that can come up in the kitchen but to time them with the rest of the order seemed almost overwhelming.  After much deliberation and thinking we finally made up our minds.

    My meal:
    Dungenous crab salad with citrus, avocado, and Meyer lemon chive vinaigrette.
    Roast Maine lobster with potato puree, shitake mushrooms, corn and tarragon
    Roasted Loin of Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spatzle
    Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream

    The dishes were beautifully done, each one had a unique and different flavor, they were amazing.  The lemon and chive vinaigrette on paper caught me off guard, I didn't expect it to have such a mild herbiness brought about by the lemon zest and chives, it went perfect with the crab.  Roasted Lobster and mushrooms, individually I love love each of them, on one plate and making it so I don't have to get my hands dirty eating lobster, even better!  The roasted bison dish was very heavy but very moist and didn't have any gaminess, the spatzle and mushrooms once again made my tummy happy.  The dessert blew me away, buttery and rich, but with a sweet and little tart huckleberries against the creaminess of the ice cream.  An amazing end to the meal.

    Her Meal:
    Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms and lemon soy dressing
    Mushroom dusted sea scallops with English pea puree, shimeji mushrooms and Meyer lemon
    Quail stuffed with foie gras, leeks and quinoa, farro, maitake mushrooms, zucchini and roasted red pepper.
    Baked Chocolate souffle with 2 sauces

    I only got a few bites here and there on these dishes as I was busy eating my own meal, but from what I tasted the quail and the sea scallop dishes is what really stood out.  The quail was moist, had a wonderful aroma and a great richness to it, no hint of gaminess at all.  The scallops were perfectly cooked, keeping that moist and subtle sweetness that I love.  The puree provided a nice color presentation and contributed a nice flavor to the dish as well.

    The cheese course was awesome, mind you we were both getting extremely full, and we saw the generous wedges of the cheese they were giving to everyone, and we knew we couldn't eat that much since we had dessert coming, and we had no idea what to pick, we asked if it would be OK if we got a small little taste on most of the cheeses.  I think we ended up with 8 or 9 cheeses all of them great but at this point we were so full and getting a little food coma-ish, I couldn't remember for the life of me their names.  I'll just say, if you haven't done a cheese course, definitely do it here.

    The meal as a whole was amazing, we took our time eating, and the 1st dish came out pretty quickly, but in between it was a very well timed spacing in between the courses, so we could have time to talk and digest our food.  Also after our dessert course because it was a special occasion they gave us another complementary dessert, it was this lemon mouse dessert, that one was amazing, I liked it even more then the chocolate souffle that my g/f had ordered.  Too bad it's not on the menu, I would order that every time!  After we settled the bill, they boxed up the little sweets that we were to full at the time to consume and gave us a take home cheesecake.  I can't wait to go back.  This experienced was a new measuring stick for how I view food!

    1 check-in

    2000+ rave reviews on yelp?!  My expectations were set high -- perhaps a little too high.  Or maybe I've just been spoiled by the other fine dining experiences we've had.  We were super excited after securing a reservation 2 months in advance for my husband's birthday trip into SF.

    The restaurant itself is elegantly decorated, but not quite the quiet romantic evening that I was anticipating.  The overall noise level is moderately high for a fine establishment and the tables are fairly close together - so you better hope for courteous non-obnoxious neighbors.   I also found it odd there were only two single use bathrooms - so each of the 3 times I had to visit, there was a line of 2-3 people waiting.  Hmmm....

    The service definitely stands out, as the team is there to make your dinner a true experience.  It's impeccably provided by a well orchestrated, non-intrusive, but ever watchful team.  Your bread plate is refilled with two fresh slices the second you're done.  The wine pairings are brought out for you to taste just as your next course is being served.  As we paid the check and walked out, without any prompting, my previously checked jacket was held out by the hostess for me to step right into.  If we had a valet car, it would've been pulled up front as we stepped outside.  And they send you off with a fresh baked treat for breakfast the next morning!

    Now the food.  The food is delicious and I love that you're free to choose whatever 3,4, or 5-course meal you desire.  Others have commented that the portions are generous, but I wish I had thought to order more than a 3-course appetizer/entree/dessert as I left a little hungry despite taking many many bites from my husband's courses!  (Perhaps next time I'll just order 4 entrees and a dessert.)

    I got:
    1. Foie gras - Melt in your mouth delicious!
    2. The famed roast Maine lobster and potato puree - Delicious, but the itty bitty lobster was a little disappointing.  And unfortunately I've been spoiled by Joel Robuchon's heavenly mashed potatoes.
    3.  Chocolate soufflé  - this was probably the biggest disappointment as it was so small (size of a mug) and not the rich flavor I was hoping for.  (If you're ever in NYC, La Grenouille has the best/biggest chocolate souffle)

    He got:
    1. Dungenness crab salad - tasty meaty fresh crab.
    2. Branzini - fish that I've never heard of but was perfectly cooked with crispy skin.
    3. Pork belly and tenderloin - moist and full of flavor.
    4. Beef filet - As someone who loves her steak, this was also nothing special but good.
    All complemented by perfect wine pairings.

    Was it good?  Yes.  Was it out of this world?  No.  Is it worth the bill?  I can think of other places I'd rather go.  Will we be back?  Jury's still out on that one.

    dare I break the 5 star streak this place has? Umm.. yeah!, ........ just keeping it real.

    I thought it was good, but not outstanding and sadly, not memorable. The menu items sound a lot better than they taste.

    We had:

    1) Lobster Salad with Avocado, Grapefruit, Watercress, Pomegranate and Mustard-Tarragon Seeds: someone overdid it with the rock salt, it was very salty. The lobster was undercooked, it was hard to cut into and chew. The blood oranges were a nice touch.

    2) Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Salsify and Lettuce Cream: this did was very nice. the sauce on it was amazing

    3) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelles, Edamame Beans  and Tarragon: this lobster was done better than the lobster on my lobster salad however, it was just an Okay dish. I thought the edamame on it was awkward and overall the dish was a bit bland.

    4) Pan Steamed Shellfish with Thai Red Curry and Jasmine Rice: I liked this dish the most out of all the dishes. The curry was light and there was a good mixture of seafood ( scallops, clams, oysters, shrimp and squid).

    5) Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celery Root-Garlic Purée and Cardamom Poached Pears : This dish was not bad. My duck was a little favorless. The poached pear in it added a nice flavor but when I ran out of the pear, I had to put the rest of the duck on my friends plate to look like I ate it

    6) Seared Filet of Beef with Potato Gratin, Roasted Eggplant-Pepper Marmalade and Soy-Mustard: it was supposed to be medium rare but I think I saw it moving, I almost called red cross to tell them my filet can be a blood doner.

    7) Guinea Hen Breast with Braised Leg, Chestnut Gnocchi, Brussels Sprouts, Apples and Pancetta:  umm, tasted like chicken.

    8) Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce: The crust on the Salmon was good but overall, horseadish and dijon - the flavors were too overwhelming.

    9) French Macaroon Ice Cream Sandwiches with Three Sauces: good

    10) Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces : This was very good, I couldn't finish it all though, it was chocolate overload for me.

    The service was very good all night which justifies the stars. The atmosphere was also very nice however, a little too "romantic" for me. I'm not here to gaze into my dates eyes, I'm here to make sure the food is worth the money.

    One thing that I thought was funny all night was the knife that they gave us to cut the food . It was more like an elongated spoon!, it was so dull, I think my biceps are bigger now since I had to use force to cut into my duck and lobster because the knife wasn't doing much.

    $300 for a forgettable meal. I hope they use some of that money to buy better knives =)

    overall, I just didn't think the food lived up to all the hype. sorry.

    Service. Like secrets agents prowling every step of the President, the wait staff is attentive, in a good way. Returning from a break to the wash room, my white table cloth napkin is folded. The bathroom is an experience in itself. Looking like a gala bathroom at a showcase South of Market, it provides a Zen like ambiance before the feast. With a smile and excitement, the wait staff explains dishes and readily available for suggestions. Danko is a great spot to wow your date with out the over the top gala of Ritz Carlton Dining Room.

    hint: When ordering at fine dining restaurant, choose dishes that you would not make at home. Take the chef for a test drive. Also, use ingredients that you may not prepare yourself. For Fear Factor thrill seekers, try the frog legs that don't disappoint. Unlike Michael Minna's, Danko has a menu that lets you be the boss. We each ordered the 3 course menu. You can order two main entrees and one appetizer if you feel like opting out on dessert. That's classy. I would best describe the cuisine as French with hints of Californian. For cheese lovers, don't miss out on their extensive cheese menu.

    Food. Prices are reasonable. (3 courses-$65,4 courses-$81, 5-courses$96)
    Dining with four people total, we order an array of dishes so that we can taste a myriad of flavors and textures. The foie gras makes me cry on the inside. With a velvety rich texture, it literally melts in your mouth. The pungent taste overwhelmed the palate while the after taste echoes throughout all the pivot points in your mouth. With a slight crispy crust, the frog legs were meaty and charmingly supported with lentil. The frog legs are a far cry from your the ones wok-fried in Chinatown.

    Stealing the appetizer show, the lobster risotto put me in comfort food heaven. With a creamy consistency, the see sweet lobster provided bouncy crunch that was a marriage made in heaven. The quail stuffed with mushroom and foie gras was another of my favorite dishes. Assemble small portion of earthy mushroom combined with buttery foie gras- all stuffed inside a moist quail. The result, amazingly. The savory sauce rounded out the dish.

    6/25/2008Previous review

    Okay for the first course I'm going to talk about the atmosphere, the second course will be the service, the third course will be the food, and the 4th will be my overall impressions.

    First Course - Atmosphere
    I was here on a crowded Wednesday night. For fine dining in SF, this is the best atmosphere I've seen. The colors were so warm and inviting, and the flower arrangements were beautiful. I liked the shape of the tables (I'm not a big fan of round tables), and I like the facts that tables were fairly close together and it was pretty noisy.

    Second Course - Service
    A+++ Best service I've ever had at a place like this. Every single server was friendly, not at all stuffy or arrogant, and really just made you feel comfortable. Shout out to Shamus, the Irish captain who is probably my favorite server of all time. We talked about Eurocup! Also, although I didn't get the cheese course, he added a cheese to my boyfriend's plate AND brought me a complimentary glass of wine to go with it. On top of that, he let me go back and see the kitchen/compliment the chefs. Shamus is now my homie.

    Third Course - Food
    B+ So don't get me wrong, the flavors are spot on. Very delicious flavors. However, I will say that the flavor combinations are less creative than other places I've seen, and the overall presentation is not quite as sophisticated. However, for those of you that get tired of having servings the size of peas, Danko is quite generous with the portion sizes. Lets go dish by dish!

    1) The tuna - beautiful presentation, very delicious.
        WINNER - The oysters with caviar - really perfect flavors, and hey, caviar never hurts.

    2) Seared Foie Gras - The flavor combination was just PERFECT. Very delicious and a large piece of foie, but I felt that there could have been a better sear-foie ratio.

    3) Horseradish crusted salmon medallion - a little dry, honestly nothing special here
        WINNER - pancetta wrapped frog legs. This was in fact my favorite dish of the night.

    4) Roasted Loin of Bison - The sauce was so good I ate all of it off of my boyfriends plate. However, the rest of the dish was nothing I haven't seen before.
       WINNER - Wild mushroom stuffed quail - quite good but could've been better, a little underseasoned.

    5) Cheese - The blue cheese from Ireland is the best one, I forgot the name though! Other than that, just go to Cheeseboard people!

    6) WINNER:  Trio of Creme Brulee - wow! these are 3 full creme brulees, not bites people! You need a big stomach for this. My favorite one was the normal one with fresh fruit on the inside. The chocolate wasn't amazing
    Chocolate Souffle - Sorry, but I make a better souffle. It's not that it was bad, or eggy, but that it was a little bit too wet and heavy on the inside.

    Fourth Course - Overall Impression
    Overall, I'd say the food was more pedestrian than say Michael Mina or the Dining Room, and if you're looking for something you've never seen before, this is not the place. HOWEVER, it was still really delicious, generous, and the atmosphere and service alone makes this place worth going to numerous times.

    Gary Danko.

    Gary Mother Fuckin' Danko.

    It goes without saying that our experience with Gary was flawless perfection. If a gay unicorn swinging from a rainbow shit Skittles into your mouth it could not be more magical than dining at Gary Danko.

    We made our reservation 2 months in advanced and the build up could not have been more pressurized. The fact that GD exceeded my incredibly high expectations speaks volumes.

    As you approach the restaurant the underplayed theme and the blacked out windows give you a supreme sense of entitlement. It's like GD begins to spoil you before you even walk through the door.

    The doorman, hosts, waitstaff, sommelier, and affineur were flawless, humble, friendly and perfect. They make you feel so welcome. They treat every selection that you make off the menu as the best selection of the evening (and you BELIEVE them whole heartedly).

    I love food. In fact, that is an understatement, I worship food. But I have never known food like GD presented food. GD changed my life with the following 5 course meal:

    To Clean the pallet we were invited to start with Champagne and the Cauliflower puree and marinated endive. The puree was delectably creamy and flavorful. This was the perfect teaser and you are left waiting with baited breath to see what will happen next.

    We ordered two wines with dinner. First a lighter Pinot (Hirsch Vineyard 2007) then a more boisterous Syrah (2005). Both amazing recommendations from the sommelier.

    As my first I chose the Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, FrisÈe and Pancetta. The egg was a masterpiece, lightly breaded and perfectly cooked. When you broke the yolk it mixed beautifully with the white polenta for an amazingly rich texture and taste. The mushrooms in the dish where probably my favorite element, so flavorful and rich.

    For my second I choose the Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Brussels Sprouts, Bacon, Parsnip PurÈe and Maple Cider Glaze. The Pork Belly was hands down my favorite dish of the evening. The glaze was out of this world; it gave the crust on the meat the perfect crunch complimented by the buttery, tender, melt in your mouth meat that hit your tongue like heaven.

    My third was the Braised Lamb Shoulder and Herb Crusted Loin with Barley Stew, Red Pepper Relish and Cumin Yogurt. The barley was cooked to perfection; so tender with the perfect flavor to compliment the meat yet underwhelm the cumin yogurt. The cumin yogurt certainly carried this plate - it was delicious. The perfect bite of tender meat, barley and cumin yogurt was enough to pledge my future unwanted first born child to GD.

    The most awaited part of the evening for me was the much anticipated Cheese Cart. A Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside. I literally died and found heaven on this cheese cart. You get to choose 4 cheeses that are served with walnut raisin bread and fresh red grapes. I suggest that you and your dining partner each choose 4 different cheeses and then share accordingly. The cheese experience is amazing!

    And then there was dessert. How I had room for dessert, is beyond me, but how could you not? The French Macaron Ice Cream Sandwiches with Three Sauces was to die for sinful. I cannot put into words how amazing the cookies where, they where literally something I have never experienced before. You are served three mini sandwiches. They were crunchy, melty, gooey perfection. The ice cream was very mild in taste and the sauces complimented each cookie flavor perfectly. My favorite was the pistachio cookie with chocolate sauce. Divine.

    You think you are done, you cannot possible put one more bite of food into your mouth and you are expecting the bill, but no, instead your server places a silver platter of delicate hand made candies on your table and you groan out of pure satiated pain. Luckily, they understand how you feel at this point and they politely offer to wrap the candies up for you in the perfect to go container.

    BUT WAIT...they still aren't done completely impressing the fuck out of you. They also send you home with a gorgeously wrapped "breakfast bread." YOU HAVE GOT TO BE KIDDING ME! Oh, GD, you really think of everything!

    By the end of the meal you completely forget that you are paying to be here and you start to profusely thank everybody that has served you like they have done you a favor like no other favor ever done.

    I never wanted to leave!

    I thought that I would be leaving still hungry and considerably poorer (yet gloriously happy). WRONG. I was more stuffed than I have ever been in my life and when the bill came I was pleasantly less shocked than I had prepared myself for. This 2.5 hour, 5 course meal doesn't fuck around. GD certainly takes food VERY seriously, and I adore him for that.

    Once in a lifetime experience? Screw that! When can I go back???

    8/25/2011

    1 check-in

    3.5 stars rounding down to 3.

    We made a RSVP about 1.5 mo before and of course the only thing available on a Sat. night is 930pm.

    1st thing I realized is how hidden it is. I've probably passed by it tons of times and never realized it was there. Add in the blackout windows and its only recognizable by a little plaque next to the front door.

    We were greeted warmly at the door and shown to our seat with just a moment's wait. My first impression was that the restaurant was a lot smaller than I thought. The second was that the decor was pretty simple and nothing spectacular. The third, and most annoying, was that the tables were VERY close to each other. This prompted servers bumping me with their ass every time they served the table next to me. That got annoying pretty quick.

    The menu was given to us and the server was very patient going over the choices, giving her recommendations, and answering our questions. We took about 15 minutes to decide while our amouse bouch (gazpacho) sat thankfully cold in front of us. Its nice to have so many choices and to choose anything on the menu as a course although not good for indecisive people like me. Finally we make our selections and begin salivating and what was to come.

    What we quickly noticed was that there were no more amouse bouch(es). I'm used to at least 3-4 throughout the meal but none showed up throughout the night. That was disappointing.

    What made up for it was the nice portion size of all the dishes. They were definitely hefty and we were pretty full by the time our 4th course came out (we had 5 each). This allowed us to share with each other more effectively and without feeling as bad ;)

    The food was good but not spectacular unfortunately. All the seafood dishes were fresh (Crab salad, broiled lobster, lobster risotto) but the meats were just ok (Pork belly, duck). Risotto was more watery than normal and pork belly seemed overcooked and didnt melt in my mouth.   Dessert didnt save it either as the creme brule was very strong of liqueur and the cheesecake was more sour and too fluffy.

    About 2.5 hours later, and some great company, we finished our meal and surveyed the damage. The price is reasonable and typical for a 5 course "fancy" meal and again the portion size is what saved a star. However, the lack of originality and mediocre execution of the food, close tables, unexciting decor, and just average service adds up to a 3 star review.
